   104вҶ’## Installation and Docs
   106вҶ’Install using `go get github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror`.
   107вҶ’
   108вҶ’Full documentation is available at
   109вҶ’https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror
   110вҶ’
   111вҶ’### Requires go version 1.13 or newer
   113вҶ’`go-multierror` requires go version 1.13 or newer. Go 1.13 introduced
   114вҶ’[error wrapping](https://golang.org/doc/go1.13#error_wrapping), which
   115вҶ’this library takes advantage of.
   116вҶ’
   117вҶ’If you need to use an earlier version of go, you can use the
   118вҶ’[v1.0.0](https://github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/tree/v1.0.0)
   119вҶ’tag, which doesn't rely on features in go 1.13.
   120вҶ’
   121вҶ’If you see compile errors that look like the below, it's likely that
   122вҶ’you're on an older version of go:
   123вҶ’
   124вҶ’```
   125вҶ’/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:112:9: undefined: errors.As
   126вҶ’/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:117:9: undefined: errors.Is
   127вҶ’```
   128вҶ’
   129вҶ’## Usage
   131вҶ’go-multierror is easy to use and purposely built to be unobtrusive in
   132вҶ’existing Go applications/libraries that may not be aware of it.
   133вҶ’
   134вҶ’**Building a list of errors**
   135вҶ’
   136вҶ’The `Append` function is used to create a list of errors. This function
   137вҶ’behaves a lot like the Go built-in `append` function: it doesn't matter
   138вҶ’if the first argument is nil, a `multierror.Error`, or any other `error`,
   139вҶ’the function behaves as you would expect.
   140вҶ’
   141вҶ’```go
   142вҶ’var result error
   143вҶ’
   144вҶ’if err := step1(); err != nil {
   145вҶ’	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   146вҶ’}
   147вҶ’if err := step2(); err != nil {
   148вҶ’	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   149вҶ’}
   150вҶ’
   151вҶ’return result
   152вҶ’```
   153вҶ’
   154вҶ’**Customizing the formatting of the errors**
   155вҶ’
   156вҶ’By specifying a custom `ErrorFormat`, you can customize the format
   157вҶ’of the `Error() string` function:
   158вҶ’
   159вҶ’```go
   160вҶ’var result *multierror.Error
   161вҶ’
   162вҶ’// ... accumulate errors here, maybe using Append
   163вҶ’
   164вҶ’if result != nil {
   165вҶ’	result.ErrorFormat = func([]error) string {
   166вҶ’		return "errors!"
   167вҶ’	}
   168вҶ’}
   169вҶ’```
   170вҶ’
   171вҶ’**Accessing the list of errors**
   172вҶ’
   173вҶ’`multierror.Error` implements `error` so if the caller doesn't know about
   174вҶ’multierror, it will work just fine. But if you're aware a multierror might
   175вҶ’be returned, you can use type switches to access the list of errors:
   176вҶ’
   177вҶ’```go
   178вҶ’if err := something(); err != nil {
   179вҶ’	if merr, ok := err.(*multierror.Error); ok {
   180вҶ’		// Use merr.Errors
   181вҶ’	}
   182вҶ’}
   183вҶ’```
   184вҶ’
   185вҶ’You can also use the standard [`errors.Unwrap`](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/#Unwrap)
   186вҶ’function. This will continue to unwrap into subsequent errors until none exist.
   187вҶ’
   188вҶ’**Extracting an error**
   189вҶ’
   190вҶ’The standard library [`errors.As`](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/#As)
   191вҶ’function can be used directly with a multierror to extract a specific error:
   192вҶ’
   193вҶ’```go
   194вҶ’// Assume err is a multierror value
   195вҶ’err := somefunc()
   196вҶ’
   197вҶ’// We want to know if "err" has a "RichErrorType" in it and extract it.
   198вҶ’var errRich RichErrorType
   199вҶ’if errors.As(err, &errRich) {
   200вҶ’	// It has it, and now errRich is populated.
   201вҶ’}
   202вҶ’```
   203вҶ’
   204вҶ’**Checking for an exact error value**
   205вҶ’
